Wash and dry produce.

Separate @prosciutto{2%ounce} from sheets and halve crosswise. Heat a drizzle of
@cooking oil{drizzle} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add prosciutto in a
single layer. Cook until browned and crisped, ~{2-3%minutes} per side, working
in batches if needed.

> TIP: Press down on prosciutto with a spatula for even crisping. If prosciutto
> starts to brown too quickly, lower heat.

Turn off heat; transfer prosciutto to a paper-towel-lined #plate{} (reserve pan
for next step). When cool enough to handle, roughly chop.

While prosciutto cooks, quarter @lemon{1}. For extra-lemony flavor, zest lemon
before quartering.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @ricotta cheese{4%ounce}, juice from two lemon
wedges (four wedges for 4 servings), a drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle}, @salt{},
and @pepper{}. For extra-lemony flavor, add half the lemon zest.

Bring 2 cups @water{2%cups} to a boil in pan used for prosciutto (no need to
wipe out pan first!). Once water is boiling, gently separate @fresh fettuccine{7%ounce}
using your hands, then add to pan. Cook, stirring constantly, until al dente,
~{5-7%minutes}.

Halve and toast @ciabatta bread{1}. Spread @butter{1%tbsp} over cut sides of
ciabatta. Halve each piece diagonally into quarters.

Once fettuccine is done, remove pan from heat. Add @pesto{4%tablespoon} and half
the prosciutto to pan; toss to combine. Taste and season with @salt{} and
@pepper{} if desired.

Divide pasta between plates. Top with a dollop of lemony ricotta, remaining
prosciutto, and a squeeze of lemon juice. Serve with ciabatta toasts and any
remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> TIP: For extra-lemony flavor, sprinkle remaining lemon zest over the top.